description.narrative: The COVID pandemic and associated protocols have underscored the critical role of parents and families as the first and primary responders for young children in Uganda. Not only have they been the anchors providing the required care, safety and psychosocial support but are also the main drivers of the demand for services. Although parents are being supported through radio talk shows to help young children to understand and cope with the COVID crisis, low prioritization of early learning during COVID closures has severely compromised standardization of guidance and coordination of service providers to maintain continuity of learning through alternative modalities. | Status:Constrained | As-of Date:30/06/2020
